  "prompt_text": "Derive the quadratic formula from the general form ax^2 + bx + c = 0.",
  "response_text": "To derive the quadratic formula from the general form \\(ax^2 + bx + c = 0\\), we will follow these steps:\n\n1. **Start with the general form**: \n   \\[ax^2 + bx + c = 0\\]\n\n2. **Move the constant term to the right side**:\n   \\[ax^2 + bx = -c\\]\n\n3. **Divide every term by \\(a\\) (assuming \\(a \\neq 0\\))**:\n   \\[x^2 + \\frac{b}{a}x = -\\frac{c}{a}\\]\n\n4. **Complete the square on the left side**:\n   To complete the square, we add and subtract \\(\\left(\\frac{b}{2a}\\right)^2\\) inside the equation:\n   \\[x^2 + \\frac{b}{a}x + \\left(\\frac{b}{2a}\\right)^2 = -\\frac{c}{a} + \\left(\\frac{b}{2a}\\right)^2\\]\n\n5. **Simplify the left side into a perfect square trinomial**:\n   \\[\\left(x + \\frac{b}{2a}\\right)^2 = -\\frac{c}{a} + \\frac{b^2}{4a^2}\\]\n\n6. **Combine the terms on the right side over a common denominator**:\n   \\[\\left(x + \\frac{b}{2a}\\right)^2 = \\frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a^2}\\]\n\n7. **Take the square root of both sides**:\n   \\[x + \\frac{b}{2a} = \\pm \\sqrt{\\frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a^2}}\\]\n   \\[x + \\frac{b}{2a} = \\pm \\frac{\\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}\\]\n\n8. **Isolate \\(x\\)**:\n   \\[x = -\\frac{b}{2a} \\pm \\frac{\\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}\\]\n   \\[x = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}\\]\n\nThus, the quadratic formula is:\n\\[x = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}\\]\n\n---\n\nVCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 8\nY (Affective Modeling): 7\nF (Flex",
